# Project Sarthi

### Technical Design Document

### Version 1.0 (Working Draft)

---

# 1. Vision

Software projects rarely fail because developers forget how to write code.

They fail because developers lose understanding.

As projects grow, knowledge becomes fragmented across multiple places:

* Source code
* Git history
* API documentation
* Database schemas
* Architecture diagrams
* README files
* Markdown notes
* External documentation
* Memory

When a developer returns to a project after several weeks or months, the code still exists, but the understanding does not.

Developers spend a significant amount of time answering questions such as:

* Where was I working?
* How does this module work?
* Why was this architecture chosen?
* Which files are connected?
* What depends on this service?
* Is the documentation still accurate?
* What changed since I last worked on this?

Project Sarthi exists to answer these questions.

Instead of acting as another project management tool or documentation platform, Sarthi continuously constructs an understanding of a software project and presents that understanding through interactive visualizations and contextual summaries.

Its purpose is not to replace GitHub, VS Code, Postman or Notion.

Its purpose is to become the layer that understands how they all relate to one another.

---

# 2. Product Identity

Project Sarthi is a Software Understanding Platform.

It continuously analyzes a software project, constructs an internal representation of it, and helps developers understand, navigate and continue development without losing context.

The project focuses on understanding software rather than producing software.

---

# 3. Core Promise

> Understand, navigate and continue any supported software project without losing context.

Every feature implemented in Sarthi must strengthen this promise.

If a feature does not help the user understand their project or continue working on it more efficiently, it does not belong in the product.

---

# 4. Elevator Pitch

Project Sarthi is a personal engineering companion that continuously builds an understanding of your software project.

Connect your GitHub repository and Sarthi automatically analyzes your codebase, APIs, database models, documentation and project structure to create an interactive project graph.

Instead of searching through hundreds of files, developers can explore their project visually, understand dependencies, identify affected components and resume work after long breaks within minutes.

Git remembers what changed.

Project Sarthi remembers what the software means.

---

# 5. Target Audience

The initial version is designed for:

* Individual software developers
* College students building projects
* Freelancers
* Open source contributors
* Indie hackers

Future versions may support collaborative teams, but collaboration is explicitly outside the scope of Version 1.

---

# 6. The Problem

Modern software development is fragmented.

A single project often involves:

* GitHub
* VS Code
* Browser tabs
* API documentation
* Database schema
* Architecture diagrams
* README files
* Markdown notes

Each tool understands one small part of the project.

No tool understands the project as a whole.

As development progresses:

* documentation becomes outdated
* architecture evolves
* dependencies increase
* modules become interconnected
* developers forget implementation details
* onboarding becomes slower
* returning to old projects becomes frustrating

Existing tools store information.

They rarely explain relationships.

Project Sarthi solves this problem by continuously maintaining a live understanding of the project.

---

# 7. Non-Goals

Project Sarthi is intentionally **not** the following:

* A replacement for GitHub
* A replacement for VS Code
* A replacement for Notion
* A replacement for Postman
* A project management tool
* A Kanban board
* A sprint planner
* A task management application
* A note-taking application
* A code editor
* A CI/CD platform

These responsibilities already have mature solutions.

Project Sarthi complements them instead of replacing them.

---

# 8. Design Philosophy

The following principles guide every engineering decision.

## Principle 1 — Passive Before Active

The user should never spend unnecessary time maintaining Project Sarthi.

Information should be imported, parsed, inferred and generated automatically whenever possible.

Manual data entry should always be considered a last resort.

---

## Principle 2 — Everything Answers a Question

Every screen should answer a meaningful question.

Examples include:

* How does authentication work?
* Which modules depend on Redis?
* Which frontend pages consume this API?
* Which documentation is outdated?
* Where did I stop working?
* What changed since my last session?

The product should avoid displaying information without purpose.

---

## Principle 3 — Everything Is Connected

Information should never exist in isolation.

Routes connect to controllers.

Controllers connect to services.

Services connect to database models.

Database models connect to documentation.

Documentation connects to architecture.

Everything ultimately becomes part of a single Project Graph.

---

## Principle 4 — One Source of Truth

Every entity inside the software project should exist exactly once inside the internal Project Graph.

All visualizations, summaries, timelines and dependency views are generated from this single source of truth.

---

## Principle 5 — Opinionated Simplicity

Project Sarthi intentionally limits customization.

Developers should not need to design their own workspace before becoming productive.

The product should provide one clear and intuitive workflow that minimizes cognitive load.

---

# 9. MVP Scope

Version 1 focuses exclusively on modern TypeScript web applications.

Supported technologies:

Frontend

* React
* Next.js

Backend

* Express.js

Languages

* TypeScript
* JavaScript

Database

* Prisma
* Mongoose

Documentation

* Markdown

API Specifications

* OpenAPI

Additional frameworks will be added later through the plugin architecture.

---

# 10. Success Criteria

The MVP will be considered successful if it can achieve the following scenario.

A developer connects an unfamiliar repository.

Within approximately five minutes they should be able to answer:

* What does this project do?
* How is it organized?
* What modules exist?
* How are those modules connected?
* How does a request travel through the system?
* Which frontend pages consume each API?
* Which database models support each feature?
* What changed since the last working session?
* Where should development continue?

without manually exploring the source code.

If Project Sarthi can consistently reduce project understanding from hours to minutes, it has achieved its primary objective.

---

# 11. Future Vision

The long-term vision is to make Project Sarthi the software understanding layer that sits above existing development tools.

Rather than replacing established tools, Sarthi continuously builds and maintains an evolving understanding of the project, making complex software easier to navigate, maintain and extend.

Future versions may introduce:

* AI-assisted explanations
* Team collaboration
* Live synchronization
* Additional language plugins
* Code quality insights
* Architecture recommendations
* Debugging assistance
* Performance analysis
* Deployment visualization

However, every future feature must continue serving the same core mission:

Help developers understand their software instead of merely storing it.



